document.text: Overview: Administer data sources, manage access control, define users, and configure audit logs. This section covers security settings, user management, and compliance for your data environment.

Overview: Displays summaries of recent threat alerts, recent detection rule findings, and recent threat intel findings, offering quick access to get started guide, discover, threat detection and threat intelligence
Get started with access control: Get started with access control, including setting up roles, permissions, and user authentication. Learn the basics of securing your OpenSearch Dashboards.
Authentication and authorization: Set up authentication and authorization sequences for users and roles. Configure how users log in and what actions they are permitted to perform within the system.
Internal users: Define and manage internal users to control access to your data. Create, edit, and delete user accounts, assigning them to specific roles and permissions.
Permissions: Controls access to individual actions and action groups. Define granular permissions to secure specific functionalities, indices, or documents within OpenSearch.
Roles: Control access to the cluster by defining roles. Map users to roles to gain permissions, manage what users can see and do within OpenSearch Dashboards and the cluster.
Audit logs: Configure audit logging for system access activities. Monitor user actions, track security events, and ensure compliance by recording all relevant operations.
Overview: Customize the appearance of the application, change feature behavior. This includes general settings, UI customization, and application preferences.
Application settings: Customize the appearance and behavior of OpenSearch Dashboards. Personalize themes, layouts, data display options, and other application-wide configurations.
Workspaces: Organize collaborative projects in use-case-specific workspaces. Create, manage, and navigate isolated environments for different teams or projects.

Assets: Manage and share global assets such as dashboards, index patterns, and visualizations. This section allows you to administer saved objects and shared resources across your OpenSearch Dashboards instance.
Overview: Overview of observability features. Understand how to monitor, troubleshoot, and gain insights into the performance and health of your applications and infrastructure.
Get started: Get started with collecting and monitoring observability data. Learn the initial steps to set up data ingestion for logs, metrics, and traces.
Discover: Analyze your data in OpenSearch and visualize key metrics. Explore raw data, apply filters, and build queries to uncover insights and understand patterns.

Dashboards: Combine data views from any OpenSearch Dashboards app into one unified dashboard and see everything in one place. Create custom dashboards for monitoring, reporting, and data visualization.

Visualizations: Using visual elements like charts, graphs, or maps to represent and analyze data. Create various types of visualizations, including bar charts, line graphs, pie charts, and more, from your OpenSearch data.
Notebooks: Create and manage notebooks for interactive data analysis, collaboration, and storytelling. Combine code, visualizations, and text to explore and present your observability data.

Integrations: A set of pre-configured assets bundled together to facilitate monitoring and analysis. Easily integrate with various data sources and services to enhance your observability capabilities.
Services: Check service events and identify performance problems. Monitor the health and performance of individual services, view dependencies, and troubleshoot issues.
Metrics: Measure and monitor key performance indicators (KPIs). Collect, visualize, and analyze time-series metrics to track system health, resource utilization, and application performance.

Traces: Trace events and identify performance problems across distributed systems. Gain end-to-end visibility into requests, pinpoint latency, and troubleshoot errors in your application architecture.
Workspace details: Define and manage a workspace's details, including its name, description, use case, icon color, and privacy settings. Customize and configure specific workspace properties.
Collaborators: Manage workspace access and permissions for collaborators. Add or remove users, assign roles, and control who can view or edit content within a workspace.
Data sources: Create and manage data source connections to external systems. Configure connections to various data storage systems, allowing OpenSearch Dashboards to retrieve and analyze data.
Index patterns: Manage index patterns to retrieve data from OpenSearch. Define how OpenSearch Dashboards interprets and queries your data stored in OpenSearch indices.
Sample data: Get started with sample data, visualizations, and dashboards. Import pre-built datasets to quickly explore OpenSearch Dashboards features and learn by example.
AI models: Review the status of running AI models. Show deployed models

Threat alerts: Set the alert to be triggered when the detector matches one or multiple rules, and can customize the notification message. View and manage security alerts generated by detectors and correlation rules.

Findings: View and manage security findings generated by detectors. Analyze findings through a bar graph (grouped by log type or rule severity) and a detailed list. You can filter by severity and log type, view finding details, explore surrounding documents in the Discover panel, and identify correlated findings to understand threat scenarios.

Correlations: The correlation graph is a security findings knowledge graph. It provides a visualization of information generated by the correlation engine and allows you to focus on specific correlations and inspect them in greater detail.
Threat detectors: Identify relevant security findings and potential threats from log data, determine what to look for and how to respond to those threats
Detection rules: Identify threat scenarios for different log sources

Correlation rules: Define threat scenarios involving multiple systems in an infrastructure by matching the signatures of threat events occurring in different log types. Once a rule contains at least two different log sources and the preferred fields and field values that define an intended threat scenario, the correlation engine can query the indexes specified in the correlation rule and identify any correlations between the findings.

Threat intelligence: Integrate your threat intelligence feeds. Feeds comprise indicators of compromise (IOCs), which search for malicious indicators in your data by setting up threat intelligence monitors. These monitors generate findings and can send notifications when malicious IPs, domains, or hashes from the threat intelligence feeds match your data. Actions: Setup threat intel sources, Set up the scan for your log sources, Configure scan to monitor threats, Add threat intel source

Log types: Log types represent the different data sources used for threat detection in Security Analytics. Log types are useful for categorizing or prepopulating detection rules when creating detectors from your source.
